The '''Bachelor of Accountancy''', also known as '''Bachelor of Accounting''', is the principal [[academic degree]] in [[accountancy]] in several countries, and is often the only (undergraduate) degree recognised for subsequent practice as a [[professional accountant]]; see [[First professional degree]]. It is abbreviated as '''B.Acy.''', '''B.Acc.''', or '''B. Accty.'''. It is also sometimes titled '''Bachelor of Accounting Science''' (B.Acc.Sci.) or "Baccalaureus [[WIKT:computatio#Latin|Computationis]]" (B.Compt.).<!-- or "Baccalaureus [[WIKT:ratio#Latin|Rationum]]" (B.Rat.). -->
The B.Acy. is extremely specialized: the [[curriculum]] requires study sufficient for professional practice (often at the [[academic major|major-level]]) in [[financial accounting]], [[management accounting]], [[auditing]], ''and'' [[taxation]]. The curriculum also includes intermediate coursework in [[business law]] and [[economics]], and general coverage of [[management|management theory]], and [[business mathematics]] and [[Business statistics|-statistics]]. The degree is thus not to be confused with a [[Bachelor of Business Administration#Program content|B.B.A. in Accounting]] or [[Bachelor of commerce#Areas of study|B.Com. in Accounting]], which are general business degrees with accounting as an area of concentration; for discussion, see {{section link|Business education|Undergraduate education}}. Some programs allow for specializations in topics such as [[Tax accounting in the United States|Tax Accountancy]], Auditing or [[Forensic accounting|Forensic Accountancy]].
Due to the specialised nature of the B.Acy., it is a professional degree course that is offered infrequently. In the [[United States]], it is likely to be a four-year undergraduate degree. In other parts of the world, such as [[Singapore]], it will be a three-year [[undergraduate]] degree. In [[Malta]], it is a two-year course that can be taken after qualifying in [[Bachelor of Commerce]] only for students who obtain exceptional grades in their previous course. Most [[List of universities in South Africa#Public universities|public universities in South Africa]] offer the degree or a variant, often as a [[Bachelor of Commerce#Honours Bachelor of Commerce|postgraduate Honours degree]].
After completion of the Bachelor of Accountancy, students typically go on to work as accountants in industry, and/or pursue [[professional accountant]] status. When the degree is recognized for this purpose, graduates will therefore pursue the [[Certified Public Accountant|CPA]] or [[Chartered Accountant|C.A.]] (or other) designations, and thus take up [[Articled clerk|"articles"]] at an [[:Category:Accounting firms|accounting firm]] accredited for training, so as to meet the relevant [[Certified Public Accountant#Work experience requirement|work experience requirements]], and will then also sit the associated [[Uniform Certified Public Accountant Examination|Professional Examination]].
Note that in the [[United States]], a bachelor's degree in accountancy is generally not sufficient for practice as a [[professional accountant]].<ref>[http://nasba.org/education/becomingacpa/ Becoming a CPA], [[National Association of State Boards of Accountancy|nasba.org]]</ref><ref>[https://community.thiswaytocpa.com/allgroups/exam-and-licensure/b/articles/archive/2012/12/28/licensure-checklist.aspx The basic things you need before they’ll crown you CPA] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408215011/https://community.thiswaytocpa.com/allgroups/exam-and-licensure/b/articles/archive/2012/12/28/licensure-checklist.aspx |date=2014-04-08 }}, thiswaytocpa.com</ref> Also, employers in industry generally prefer to hire applicants with a master's in accountancy (or an [[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A.]] with a concentration in accounting) and/or with professional certification.<ref>{{cite web|title=How to Become an Accountant or Auditor|url=http://www.bls.gov/ooh/Business-and-Financial/Accountants-and-auditors.htm#tab-4|publisher=Bureau of Labor Statistics|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> Accountancy graduates intending to work as accountants will therefore commence with the [[Master of Accountancy]]; an accelerated program, or an advanced program allowing for specialized / additional elective work, is typically available to these students.<ref>eg. [http://agsm.ucr.edu/mpac/ Anderson-Riverside]</ref>
